 Since $\triangle ABC \sim \triangle PAQ$, we have $m\angle BAC = m\angle PQA$. So, $m\angle PQA = 70^\circ$. Similarly, since $\triangle ABQ \sim \triangle QCP$, we have $m\angle ABQ = m\angle QCP$. So, $m\angle QCP = 60^\circ$. Now, we know that a straight line is the sum of its interior angles. Therefore, $m\angle PQC = m\angle PQA - m\angle QCP = 70^\circ - 60^\circ = 10^\circ$.
Therefore, the answer is

